  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n- The Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 - Laundering of monetary instruments\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 - Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity\n\n3. State Level:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\nThese statutes:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish criminal penalties\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate record-keeping and reporting requirements\n- Provide tools for investigating and prosecuting financial crimes\n\nThe laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income and to disrupt organized crime, terrorist financing, and other illicit financial activities.\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and imprisonment, depending on the specific circumstances of the offense.",
